## Why this matters

DNS is allowed outbound in nearly every network — firewalls that block arbitrary TCP/UDP traffic typically permit DNS to function, making it an attractive covert channel. Adversaries abuse this in three common ways:

1. **C2 channels** — beacons embed instructions in TXT/A record responses; clients embed session data in subdomain labels.
2. **Data exfiltration** — files are chunked, base32-encoded, and transmitted as subdomain labels in queries to attacker-controlled authoritative DNS servers.
3. **DGA (domain generation algorithms)** — malware queries dozens of algorithmically generated domains per minute looking for an active C2 host.

All three patterns produce the same detectable fingerprint at the endpoint: a single process emitting many DNS queries with high subdomain entropy under a small number of parent domains. This is detectable without inspecting DNS packet contents — Sysmon Event 22 captures it from the Windows DNS client API directly.

