## Results

Running the simulation script generated 20 DNS queries to unique subdomains under `evil-lab-domain.xyz` over approximately 59 seconds. The detection SPL surfaced this cleanly:

| parent_domain | Image | count | unique_subdomains | duration_sec |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `evil-lab-domain.xyz` | `C:\Windows\System32\WindowsPowerShell\v1.0\powershell.exe` | 20 | 20 | 58.7 |

`unique_subdomains == count` (1:1 ratio) is the detection fingerprint. Combined with the originating process (`powershell.exe` issuing sustained DNS queries to a `.xyz` domain — itself unusual outside specific automation contexts), this is a high-confidence signal.

Normal background DNS traffic during the same window — `google.com`, `github.com`, `*.office.com`, `*.microsoft.com` — was correctly excluded by the `unique_subdomains >= 5` threshold, because legitimate browsing reuses domain names heavily.

