## Tuning for production

The thresholds here (`count >= 10`, `unique_subdomains >= 5`, `15m` window) are **lab-tuned for fast iteration**. Production deployment requires tuning against organizational baseline traffic, because several legitimate technologies produce superficially similar patterns:

| Source | Why it looks like a beacon |
|---|---|
| CDNs (Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly) | Many unique subdomains under one parent |
| Email security gateways | Bulk reputation lookups for hashes/URLs encoded in subdomains |
| EDR / security telemetry | Some agents use DNS for lookup of file/IP reputation |
| Antivirus updates | High-frequency manifest checks |
| DNS-based VPNs / split-horizon resolvers | Tunneling is the legitimate function |

**Recommended production adjustments:**

- Raise thresholds (start at `count >= 50` and `unique_subdomains >= 25` per 15m window)
- Maintain an allowlist of known-good parent domains for CDNs, AV vendors, EDR tools, and SaaS platforms in use
- Add an enrichment step against a domain-reputation feed (newly-registered domains weight higher)
- Correlate with originating process — `chrome.exe` querying many CDN subdomains is normal; `powershell.exe` doing it is not
- Suppress detections where the originating process is on an explicit allowlist (e.g., browser binaries, AV update services)

