## Limitations

1. **Low-and-slow beacons evade volumetric detection.** Real C2 beacons often check in every 30–60 minutes. A single query per hour will not cross any reasonable threshold. Catching slow beacons requires interval-regularity analysis (looking for unusually consistent inter-query timing) rather than volume.
2. **Encrypted DNS bypasses Sysmon Event 22 entirely.** DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) and DNS-over-TLS (DoT) traffic does not generate DNS query events because the OS DNS client isn't involved — the application resolves directly over HTTPS. Detection of DoH-based C2 requires network-layer inspection (TLS SNI, JA3 fingerprinting, or DoH endpoint blocklists).
3. **No DNS response inspection.** Sysmon Event 22 captures the query and a basic result field but does not log full TXT record contents — so payload-bearing DNS responses (the inbound C2 channel for beacons) are not visible at this layer.
4. **High false-positive potential without tuning.** As noted above, this rule will fire on legitimate CDN traffic in production environments without a maintained allowlist.

